<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-543-429  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 543 429.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  Sept 26 1990 n142 p99(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business andamp; Computer Publications(England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Teach yourself WordPerfect 5.1. (tutorial software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Zuin, Daniela.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Electrovision (products).andO;Product:   Teach Yourself WordPerfect 5.1 (Educational software).andO;Topic:     Software PackagesWord ProcessingEvaluationComputer-Assisted Instruction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Teach Yourself WordPerfect 5.1andM;There's a vast array of word processing packages on the market -- witnessthis issue's Buyer's Guide -- but familiarity with one package is noguarantee that you'll be able to navigate your way round any of the othernumerous packages you might come across, perhaps in a change of jobs.andM;The cost and time involved with external courses can easily make the prospectof learning in your own time and at your own pace very attractive.andM;This is where Teach Yourself WordPerfect 5.1 comes in.andP;  Electrovision'spackage offers users two levels of tuition.andM;The first level is really basic and designed for those who've never used aword processor before.andP;  The second is for users who are new to WordPerfectbut are old hands at similar programs.andM;The first program takes you through the steps needed to write a letter --bold typefaces and underlining included.andP;  The second program teaches youadvanced functions such as merging documents, creating macros, addinggraphics and making indexes.andM;A note in the accompanying manual promises that 'You will have created,edited, and printed your first document using WordPerfect in less than onehour'.andP;  Well, this gives some indication of how quickly the program runs butit would be wrong to assume that having achieved this, you'll be able torepeat these tasks indefinitely.andM;Interaction in this program means pressing the buttons yourself rather thanwatching blankly from the sidelines.andP;  There's no danger of anything goingwrong, because if the program asks you to press alt F4 it prevents youactually doing anything else.andP;  However, this makes it easy to go speedingalong through all the routines necessary, instantly forgetting what you'vejust done.andP;  As much as anything this is probably due to the quick successionof new commands, so it's probably a good idea to do a small amount at a timeand then practise it.andM;Both programs allow you to choose which function you want to learn next bypresenting them to you on a menu.andP;  This gives you the option to revise orskip tasks as you wish.andP;  If all else fails, help can be found in the manual'squick reference section, which documents how to execute each command.andO;</TEXT></DOC>